title: Human Brain
description: The human brain, combined with the spinal cord, makes up the central nervous system. The main regions of the brain are the cerebrum, brainstem, and cerebellum. The cerebrum is the largest part of the human brain, and has two hemispheres. The hemispheres are connected by commissural nerve tracts, such as the corpus callosum (largest). Each hemisphere is divided into the frontal, temporal, parietal, and occipital lobes. The frontal lobe handles executive functions (planning, reasoning, and abstract thought). The temporal lobe handles sensory input, derived meanings, retention of visual memory, language comprehension, and emotion association. The parietal lobe handles major sensory inputs from the skin (touch, temperature, and pain receptors). The occipital lobe handles vision processing. The brainstem connects the cerebellum to the spinal cord. The midbrain, the pons, and the medulla oblongata make up the brainstem. Underneath the cerebral cortex are structures such as the thalamus, the pineal gland, the hypothalamus, the pituitary gland, the amygdala, and the hippocampus.

title: Study Calendar
description: When studying, it’s important to keep a calendar of the many things that you have to accomplish. If you don’t already have a thorough and comprehensive calendar, here are our recommendations: First, mark off the fixed blocks of time that you can’t really change (work, class, significant events). Second, mark off the flexible blocks of time that you want to keep (gym, birthdays, brunch or dinners). Third, mark off the personal blocks of time that you need to recharge (spa, family, alone). Now, there might not be many reasonable blocks of time remaining (if you take into account meals, sleeping, transportation), but mark those as your aspirational study times! If you make it a priority, those times can be turned into progress and growth in the topics and skills that you need to ace this exam! Good luck studying. ~

title: Timed Practice
description: Often, the best test-takers are the ones who manage their time most efficiently. Skip questions (and mark or guess) that seem out of reach, spend a little more time on questions that you feel confident are nearly solved, and ensure that there’s at least time to attempt every question (so that you don’t miss any 'fast and easy' points near the end). The general rule for timing yourself while practicing is to divide your total study time into thirds. The first third, don’t use any timers, simply concentrate on learning contend and strategies (even if this is slow going). The second third, practice timed, but don’t worry if you miss a few things or still need work (that’s normal). The final third, focus on timing, and look for places that you can gain back a few seconds here or there. A classic example is in Quant: if you could do a single math step (say, multiplication or subtraction) even just one second faster, you could gain back 2-3 minutes of extra time across the average number of steps and calculations in that section. Wouldn’t that be great!

title: Human Alveoli
description: Pulmonary alveoli are the millions of hollow, distensible cavities in the lungs allowing pulmonary gas exchange. Oxygen from air is exchanged for carbon dioxide from blood (at the blood–air barrier) between the alveolar air and the pulmonary capillary. Oxygen is diffused into the capillaries to progress through the bloodstream and carbon dioxide released from the capillaries into the alveoli will be breathed out. Alveoli are more numerous in the blind-ended alveolar sacs than at the bronchioles or the walls of the alveolar ducts. Alveoli make up about 90 percent of the total lung volume.

title: Eukaryotic Animal Cell
description: Eukaryotic cells may be unicellular or multicellular, and typically contain other membrane-bound organelles such as a nucleus (purple), rough endoplasmic reticulum (tan with red dots), mitochondria (orange ovals with red squiggles), lysosomes (light blue balls), centrosome (tan tube with strands) and a Golgi apparatus (smooth tan). Eukaryotes can reproduce by mitosis (asexually) or meiosis (sexually, gamete fusion). Animal cells are different from other eukaryotes (such as plants), since they do not have cell walls and hence can transform into a variety of shapes.

title: The Cell Membrane
description: The cell membrane, or plasma membrane, separates the cell interior from the outside environment (and also protects against harm from extracellular agents). The cell membrane is a lipid bilayer, with two layers of phospholipids. Cholesterols (a lipid component, not shown) are interspersed between the layers, to maintain membrane fluidity. The membrane also contains integral proteins (green and pink, with hollow cores) that span the membrane and serve as membrane transporters, and glycolipids embedded in the outer lipid layer (orange, branched structures) that facilitate interaction with the cell's environment. The cell membrane is selectively permeable to ions and organic molecules, so controls the movement of substances in and out of cells and organelles through diffusion, facilitated diffusion, and active transport mechanisms.

title: Mitosis vs Meiosis
description: In the cell cycle, mitosis allows replicated chromosomes to be separated into two new nuclei. Cell division by mitosis creates genetically identical daughter cells, with exactly the same total number of chromosomes (one round of equational division). You can remember mitosis has ‘to’ right in the name = two daughter cells created. Contrastingly, meiosis divides germ cells in sexually-reproducing organisms, producing the gametes (sperm or egg) via a reductional division. Meiosis requires two rounds of division, resulting in four cells with one copy of each chromosome (haploid). Additionally, at the metaphase plate (prior to division), genetic material from paternal and maternal copies of each chromosome is crossed over. You can remember that meiosis has four vowels = four daughter cells created.

title: DNA Double Helix
description: Deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) has two polynucleotide chains that form a double helix. This contains genetic instructions to develop, function, grow, maintain, and reproduce all known organisms and many viruses. Nucleic acids are essential for all known forms of life (as are proteins, lipids, and complex carbohydrates). Each nucleotide strand of DNA is composed of a nitrogen-containing nucleobase: cytosine [C], guanine [G], adenine [A] or thymine [T]), as well as deoxyribose (sugar) and a phosphate group. The nucleotides are joined from the sugar of one nucleotide to the phosphate of the next, creating an alternating sugar-phosphate backbone. The nitrogenous bases are bound together as A with T (two H-bonds) or C with G (three H-bonds). In DNA, there are pyrimidines: thymine and cytosine, or purines: adenine and guanine.

title: Hemoglobin
description: Hemoglobin (Hb or Hgb) is the iron-containing oxygen-transport present in red blood cells (erythrocytes) of almost all vertebrates. Hemoglobin in human blood carries oxygen from the lungs to vascularize the tissues of the body. Hemoglobin releases oxygen to cells that require aerobic respiration, to provide the energy to power human metabolism. Hemoglobin has a quaternary structure, and most of the amino acids in hemoglobin form alpha helices connected by short non-helical segments. The center of each alpha or beta subunit is the heme group with iron (shown as a small orange ball) at the center of the porphyrin ring (nitrogen connections shown in blue).

title: Triceratops
description: Triceratops is an herbivorous dinosaur from the Late Cretaceous period. It a non-avian dinosaur, and became extinct in the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction (66 million years ago). The name Triceratops means 'three-horned face', and refers to the dinosaur’s distinctive features. Triceratops is from the Kingdom: Animalia, Phylum: Chordata, Clade: Dinosauria.

title: Glucose Ring
description: Glucose is a monosaccharide sugar with the molecular formula C6H12O6. It is the most abundant carbohydrate, and is mainly made through photosynthesis by plants and algae. In the figure, carbons (black), oxygens (red), and hydrogens (white), construct a closed ring of naturally-occurring D-glucose in the beta-D-glucopyranose (most stable) form. This is used by plants to make cellulose in cell walls or starches, though it is not digestible to humans. The alpha-D-glucopyranose (less stable) form is what humans process most readily.

title: Bean (Dicot) Seedling
description: A seedling develops out of a plant embryo from a seed, after germination of the seed. Seedlings have three main parts: radicle (embryonic root), hypocotyl (embryonic shoot), and cotyledons (seed leaves). Seedlings of some flowering plants have no cotyledons (acotyledon). The developing shoot bearing the first true leaves of a plant is the plumule. For many plants, plumule only develops once the cotyledons have grown above ground (epigeal germination). However, some seeds develop by the plumule growing up through the soil with the cotyledons remaining below ground (hypogeal germination).

title: Eukaryotic Plant Cell
description: Plant cells are contained in green plants (photosynthetic eukaryotes) in the kingdom Plantae. These cells have primary cell walls containing cellulose, hemicelluloses, and pectin. There are plastids that have the capability to perform photosynthesis and store starch. For reproduction, plant cells are absent flagella or centrioles (except in gametes), and cell division involves the formation of a cell plate (phragmoplast) that separates the new daughter cells. In the shown image, there is a nucleus (purple), smooth endoplasmic reticulum (blue), rough endoplasmic reticulum (purple dotted with red), Golgi body (tan), mitochondrion (red), vacuole (blue), chloroplast (green), and peroxisomes (red balls).

title: Bean Life Cycle
description: A legume (pea, or bean) is an angiosperm plant from the family Fabaceae or Leguminosae. This family is widely distributed, and includes trees and shrubs that have compound, stipulate leaves. This is the third-largest land plant family (by number of species), behind Orchidaceae and Asteraceae, with about 765 genera and about 20,000 known species. Fabaceae is the most common family found in tropical rainforests and dry forests of the Americas and Africa. Legumes also play an important role in agriculture and crop rotations due to the symbiotic nitrogen-fixing bacteria in their root nodule structures.

title: Adenosine Triphosphate (ATP)
description: Adenosine triphosphate (ATP, three phosphates) is an energy-rich organic compound. Many processes in living cells (muscle contraction, nerve impulse propagation, and chemical synthesis) utilize energy from ATP. When used in a metabolic process, the result is adenosine diphosphate (ADP, two phosphates), or adenosine monophosphate (AMP, one phosphate). In the molecule shown, carbon (black) and nitrogen (blue) make up the nitrogenous base (adenine), additional oxygen (red) in the sugar ribose, and phosphorus (orange) in the triphosphate, with hydrogen (white) in all remaining bonds.

title: Human Evolution
description: Human evolution led to the emergence of Homo sapiens through gradual expression of traits such as bipedalism, dexterity, and language development. Primates diverged in the Late Cretaceous (85 million years ago) from other mammals, with their earliest fossils appearing during the Paleocene (55 million years ago). Hominin subtribe Australopithecine became distinct from gorillas between 8 to 9 million years ago, and separated from the chimpanzees and bonobos between 4 to 7 million years ago. Anatomically modern humans emerged in Africa approximately 300,000 years ago.

title: Floating Island
description: While maybe a bit more extreme than the islands in the Galapagos where Darwin really hit his stride, we still thought this little floating island was fun! Hope you enjoy it and take a few deep breaths. You’re about a third of the way through the biology section! Keep up the great effort. ~

title: Darwin's Finches
description: This is not one of Darwin's finches, but a colorful relative. Galápagos finches are a group of about 18 species of passerine birds, famously diverse in beak form and function which are highly adapted to different food sources. Except for the Cocos finch (from Cocos Island) all others are found only on the Galápagos Islands. The birds vary wildly, between 10 to 20 centimeters (4 to 8 inches) in length, and between 8 and 38 grams (0.3 and 1.3 ounces) in weight. The finches are thought to have through adaptive radiation, wherein species rapidly diversify from one common ancestor. This is especially likely when there are different environments or new resources available. The speciation or phenotypic adaptation will likely show different morphological or physiological traits.

title: Trilobite Fossil
description: Trilobites are one of the earliest recorded (in fossils) groups of arthropods. The first trilobites in the fossil record are from the Early Cambrian (521 million years ago), with massive growth and diversity throughout the lower Paleozoic, then slow extermination of orders and families during the Devonian. The last trilobites appear to have fallen in the mass extinction at the end of the Permian (252 million years ago). Trilobites number some of the most successful of all animals, with a reign on Earth in oceans and shallow waters for almost 270 million years, and over 22,000 species described in the fossil records.

title: Skin Anatomy
description: Skin is an organ of the integumentary system that protects, regulates, and provides sensation. In mammals, there are multiple layers of ectodermal tissue that guard the muscles, bones, and internal organs, and subcutaneous fat (tan cluster of balls). Mammals have hair on their skin (brown follicle) that interacts with the environment, or functions as insulation. Temperature regulation can also be accomplished through sweat glands and ducts (white coils). Sensation can be at shallow or deep levels through corpuscles (green round), or nerve fibers (yellow thin). The thickness of skin also varies depending on location. In humans, the skin under and around the eyes and eyelids is the thinnest (0.5 mm).

title: Eosinophil
description: Eosinophils are white blood cells (WBCs) that combat multicellular parasites and infections in vertebrates, and aid allergy and asthma responses (with mast cells and basophils). They are granulocytes, and have large acidophilic cytoplasmic granules, develop in the bone marrow, and are terminally differentiated in blood (and do not multiply). Eosinophils make up about 2 to 3% of WBCs in human blood.

title: Monocyte
description: Monocytes are white blood cells (WBCs) that can differentiate into macrophages and dendritic cells. They are the largest type of leukocyte in blood, and can influence adaptive immune responses or tissue repair functions. Monocytes are produced by the bone marrow from precursors called monoblasts, and have an amoeboid appearance with a nongranulated cytoplasm (agranulocytes). They are mononuclear and with an ellipsoidal nucleus that is lobulated or indented (kidney-shaped). Monocytes make up 2 to 10% of WBCs in the human body.

title: Lymphocyte
description: Lymphocytes are white blood cells (WBCs) that include cell-mediated and cytotoxic immunity subtypes natural killer cells (innate), and T cells (adaptive), as well as blood-based B cells (antibody-mediated, adaptive). Lymphocytes make up 18 to 42% of WBCs in human blood. T cells that mature in the thymus and B cells that mature in the bone marrow are the primary adaptive immune response components. Both types of cells recognize specific antigens (during antigen presentation), and, once identified, the generate a response to eliminate the pathogens or infected cells. B cells make antibodies, which neutralize bacteria and viruses. T helper cells make cytokines that direct the immune response, while cytotoxic T cells make toxic enzyme granules that directly destroy infected cells. B cells and T cells remember antigens that they have seen, by forming memory cells for each specific pathogen encountered. In this way, an animal is able to have a rapid or stronger response to that same pathogen at a later time.
